Place the CHIP sys_heap buffer in .noinit rather than .bss.

On ESP32 the primary DRAM segment (dram0_0_seg, where .bss lives) is
136K after the BT controller reserve, and the radio driver kernel-pool
contributions already consume a third of it. The second bank (SRAM1)
only receives .noinit sections on this port. A heap buffer needs no
zero-initialization, so marking it __noinit relocates the entire CHIP
heap to the otherwise-underused second bank.

Upstream candidate: maybe (harmless generally, but only ESP32 needs it).

diff --git a/src/platform/Zephyr/SysHeapMalloc.cpp b/src/platform/Zephyr/SysHeapMalloc.cpp
index 7c057ac8ea..371addc014 100644
--- a/src/platform/Zephyr/SysHeapMalloc.cpp
+++ b/src/platform/Zephyr/SysHeapMalloc.cpp
@@ -22,6 +22,7 @@
 
 extern "C" {
 #include <zephyr/init.h>
+#include <zephyr/linker/section_tags.h>
 #include <zephyr/sys/math_extras.h>
 #include <zephyr/sys/mutex.h>
 #include <zephyr/sys/sys_heap.h>
@@ -38,7 +39,9 @@ namespace {
 // Choose the value that guarantees that the returned memory blocks are castable to all built-in types.
 constexpr size_t kMallocAlignment = alignof(long long);
 
-uint8_t sHeapMemory[CONFIG_CHIP_MALLOC_SYS_HEAP_SIZE] alignas(kMallocAlignment);
+// __noinit: a heap needs no zero-init, and on ESP32 this moves the buffer
+// out of the starved primary DRAM bank into the noinit-only second bank.
+uint8_t __noinit sHeapMemory[CONFIG_CHIP_MALLOC_SYS_HEAP_SIZE] alignas(kMallocAlignment);
 sys_heap sHeap;
 SYS_MUTEX_DEFINE(sLock);
 
